replies.comment info:
@Harshini K 
It took me a while to understand how the graph was organized and I wonder if there would be a better way to show that is a map of the United States. 
I also like your question about the proportion of women to men in positions of power who are making these decisions and mandates.

@Tyler Stoen 

Hey Tyler! Good work picking up on the fact that a lot of the abortion bans are in the Southern states. I noticed that too but had a hard time stating that explicitly. You worded it really well! 

I also love your headline. It's really short and snappy, perfect for an article!

@Will Kapner 
Hi Will,
I really like your question on how birth control is handled in the different states.  I wonder if the orange states even talk about alternative methods to birth control other than abstinence, as if they assume people abstain from sex, they shouldn't have any need for other forms of birth control.  If they do teach about it, what types do they focus on?

@Edy Reynolds 

Hi Edy, 

I agree with your sentiment that while the graph does communicate interesting information, it probably could have been done more effectively. I did like how the states were displayed like they would be on a map though. It helped to provide a geographic dimension to the data.

@Adam Kong 
Hi Adam, 
I also noticed the relationship between abortions and politics. In the news last year, a saw a lot of Republican politicians (usually from red states) arguing against abortion and now, a lot of those states are planning to ban it. This is especially prevalent in the southern U.S.
